As we see in the formula for the limit of the Riemann sum

\begin{align*}\lim_{N\rightarrow \infty}\sum_{k=1}^N\left(\frac{b-a}{N}\right)\cdot f\left(a+\frac{k(b-a)}{N}\right) = \int_a^bf(x)dx\end{align*}

the factor that is devided by $N$, must be $b-a$. So, we know that
$b-a = 3$.

Now we search for the variable

\begin{align*}\displaystyle x_k=a+\frac{k(b-a)}{N} = a+\frac{3k}{N}.\end{align*}

The only term, that matches this expression is

\begin{align*}-2+\frac{3k}{N}\end{align*}

and thus \emph{a} must be equal to \emph{-2}. With \emph{3=b-a = b+2} we
find that \emph{b=1}.

The last thing is to find the function \emph{f}. From the formula of the
limit of the Riemann sum we know that

\begin{align*}f\left(a+\frac{k(b-a)}{N}\right) = \left[\left(a + \frac{k(b-a)}{N}\right)^3-1\right],\end{align*}

\begin{align*}f\left(-2+\frac{3k}{N}\right) = \left(-2 + \frac{3k}{N}\right)^3-1,\end{align*}

\begin{align*}f(x) = x^3-1.\end{align*}

So the answer is \textbf{(b)},

\begin{align*}\lim_{N\rightarrow \infty}\sum_{k=1}^N\left(\frac{3}{N}\right)\cdot \left[\left(-2\frac{k3}{N}\right)^3-1\right] = \int_{-2}^1(x^3-1)dx.\end{align*}
